1️⃣ services:
services:
Meaning

This section defines containers that make up your application.

Why we use it

Docker Compose is used to run multiple containers together.

Your project has:

MySQL database

Flask application

So we define both as services.

Internally

Docker Compose will create separate containers for each service.

Example:

mysql container
flask-app container
2️⃣ mysql:
mysql:
Meaning

This is the name of the service.

Why we use it

Other containers can refer to this container using this name.

Example:

MYSQL_HOST=mysql

Flask will connect to the MySQL container using Docker DNS.

Internally

Docker automatically creates a hostname:

mysql

inside the Docker network.

3️⃣ container_name
container_name: mysql
Meaning

This defines the actual container name.

Without this, Docker Compose will generate something like:

two-tier-flask-app_mysql_1
Why we use it

To make debugging easier.

Example:

docker logs mysql
docker exec -it mysql bash
4️⃣ image
image: mysql:8
Meaning

This tells Docker which image to use.

Image = blueprint for container.

Why we use version
mysql:8

instead of

mysql:latest

Because latest can change and break applications.

Internally

Docker will:

Pull image from Docker Hub
Create container from image
5️⃣ environment
environment:
  MYSQL_DATABASE: devops
  MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD: root
Meaning

These are environment variables passed into the container.

Why MySQL needs them

MySQL image requires:

MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD

to initialize the database.

Optional variable:

MYSQL_DATABASE

creates a database automatically.

Internally

During container startup MySQL entrypoint script runs:

docker-entrypoint.sh

and reads these variables to configure the database.

6️⃣ ports
ports:
  - "3306:3306"
Meaning
host_port : container_port

Example:

3306 (host) → 3306 (container)
Why we use it

So external applications can connect to MySQL.

Example:

MySQL Workbench
DBeaver
Flask app outside Docker
Internally

Docker creates a NAT rule:

Host → Container
7️⃣ volumes
volumes:
  - mysql-data-v:/var/lib/mysql
Meaning

Attach persistent storage.

volume_name : container_path
Why this path?

MySQL stores database files in:

/var/lib/mysql
Without volume
container deleted → data lost
With volume
data stored outside container
Internally

Docker stores volume here:

/var/lib/docker/volumes/mysql-data-v/_data
8️⃣ networks
networks:
  - flask-network
Meaning

This container will connect to a custom Docker network.

Why we use it

Containers can communicate securely.

Example:

flask-app → mysql
Internally

Docker creates a bridge network.

Containers get IPs like:

172.18.0.2
172.18.0.3

But they communicate using service names.

9️⃣ restart
restart: always
Meaning

Automatically restart container if it stops.

Example scenarios
server reboot
container crash
docker daemon restart
Internally

Docker restart policy triggers container restart.

🔟 healthcheck
healthcheck:
  test: ["CMD", "mysqladmin", "ping", "-h", "localhost", "-uroot", "-proot"]
Meaning

Checks if MySQL is actually ready, not just running.

Why needed

Sometimes container is running but MySQL is not ready yet.

Example:

container started
database still initializing
This command does
mysqladmin ping

If database responds:

mysqld is alive

Container becomes healthy.

Healthcheck Timing
interval: 10s

Check every 10 seconds.

timeout: 5s

If check takes longer than 5 seconds → fail.

retries: 5

Retry 5 times before marking unhealthy.

start_period: 60s

Wait 60 seconds before starting health checks.

Because MySQL needs time to start.

